  Database_Simulation: timezone fix shipped (Option A, as you proposed)

  Status: deployed and live. Ship lockstep on your end at your convenience.

  What changed in the API

  Per your timezone bug report — Option A is now in effect. Every datetime on the wire is tz-aware ISO with offset:

  - GET /scheduling/slots returns Asia/Jerusalem:
  "start_time": "2099-06-01T09:00:00+03:00" (or +02:00 in winter, DST-aware).
  - POST /scheduling/appointments/book requires tz-aware start_time. Naive datetimes are now rejected with 422 (Pydantic validation error). You can send Asia/Jerusalem (most natural — same as what you got from /slots) or any
  other tz; the backend converts to UTC internally.
  - All appointment reads (GET /appointments/..., response of POST /book) return UTC with Z suffix:
  "start_time": "2099-06-01T06:00:00Z".
  This represents the same instant as the offered slot. Any date library (luxon, date-fns, dayjs, JS native) parses both representations and lets you compare instants directly.
  - All other timestamps (created_at, updated_at, cancelled_at, plus read_at/replied_at on Messages) are also tz-aware UTC.

  What you need to do

  Per your own prompt's "Coordination" section — you said: "For Option A: call_agent will tag outgoing times with Asia/Jerusalem and accept tz-aware responses."

  Concretely:

  1. When sending POST /scheduling/appointments/book, ensure start_time is tz-aware. If you pass through the value from /scheduling/slots, it's already +03:00-tagged — works directly. If you construct from a wall-clock string
  with implicit Jerusalem context, attach Asia/Jerusalem tzinfo before serializing.
  2. When parsing slot or appointment responses, stop assuming naive datetimes. Whichever date library you use, parse the offset (it's always present now). Compare as instants, not wall-clock strings.
  3. No URL changes — endpoint paths are unchanged.
  4. No data migration on your side — pre-existing test rows in Neon were just naive UTC values; on read they now appear with Z suffix. Same instants.

  Acceptance criterion (from your prompt)

  ▎ Books an appointment for slot 09:00 and verifies the resulting GET /appointments/by-patient row reports the same wall-clock time

  ✅ Verified locally. Slot offered as 09:00+03:00, booking stored, GET-back returns 06:00Z, and 06:00Z.astimezone(Asia/Jerusalem) == 09:00. Same instant, two representations.

  Latent input bug also fixed

  Aside: the previous code used request.start_time.replace(tzinfo=tz) which silently relabeled the caller's tz as Jerusalem. If you'd ever sent 09:00+00:00, it would have been mis-stored. That's now
  request.start_time.astimezone(UTC) — honors whatever tz you send.

